climbs.name: When Life Gives You Lemons...SQUEEZE THEM TO DEATH!

content.description:
This is a two part climb. Part one (When Life Gives You Lemons...) heads up easy terrain left of the crack to a nice stance, then traverse right with a tricky sequence, to a BOMBER hand jam, take it to the top. 

  Part two (SQUEEZE THEM TO DEATH!) heads up using the crack and big holds on the left but goes straight up the crack utilizing a wicked one knuckle pinky jam and a heinous pinch on the arete to the same BOMBER hand jam as part one.
content.protection: Standard rack. Optional #1 Ball-Nuts for part one and a micro cam for the crux piece on both parts. Solo up the left side of the buttress to set TR.
content.location: Back side of The Frigate, find Bowspirit and to your right is another buttress with a right angling crack.

content.description: The crux of the route is after the garden ledge there is a large crack that can be fist jammed or done via a lay back.  This part may be harder than a 5.3.
content.protection: The route takes good pro.  A standard rack and set of nuts.
content.location: The route is to the right of Route #20 page #238 3rd Edition Climber's Guide To Devil's Lake by Olaf and Mayer.    Route lies right of "Can Can" by about 10'.

content.description:
Starts with a boulder problem on the right face of the South arete.  You generally follow this corner up, avoiding the main crack of Can Can.  At the top, move back onto the South face into a seam. 

  The hard part is spotting the crimps - there is usually no chalk on this route.
content.protection: Some, mostly small nuts.  It is also possible to use the Can-can crack in the mid-section.
content.location: The South end of the Frigate, to the left of Can Can.

content.description:
If you use Spider Mitts you're going A0 

  It's tape or nothin' 

  One of the hardest 8's you'll ever climb
content.protection: There is a good pin near the start & then it goes standard rack

content.description: Starting left of Flying Dutchman this ascends the corner on small holds and a tricky step right over the center overhang. Then up buckets to a tricky throw on the left corner of the formation (same as FD).
content.protection: Ok gear in bottom, one at your feet for the top throw, run out in between. TR is gear in the block and then a nice hex in the block across the access chimney.
content.location: Corner left of Flying Dutchman. Pic coming soon.

content.description:
Start right of the chimney (can use the chimney for easier variation, but the chimney is not part of this route). Climb is mostly slab past the first 15 feet.  

  Belay space is very limited and bushwacked. 

This route is not listed in the guide book
content.protection: Set the top road right of the roof on the north side of The Friggate.
content.location: North side of The Friggate, right of the chimney. Using the 3rd Edition Climber's Guide To Devil's Lake by Olaf and Mayer, go to page 235, route is in between #25 and #18

content.description:
A quick scramble to the top of the Frigate, great for setting or retrieving topropes. 

  Scramble up to the saddle between the Frigate and the main bluff. Step across to the left - there are a couple of places to do this, all about the same difficulty. Move out onto the exposed East Face, and work your way up to the top, with a few 5th class moves as you move up from ledge to ledge. 

  The easiest moves could be hard to spot when you are coming down from the top.
content.location: Between the Frigate and the main bluff, on the North end.  Starts on the West side, traverses around to the East side.

content.description: Route #19 page #238 3rd Edition Climber's Guide To Devil's Lake by Olaf and Mayer.   Route lies just right of "Can Can".  Surmount short steep blockish thing to ledge then climb great finger crack/layback fissure to slabs and ledges above.  Belay (or TR anchor) at top mid section of "The Frigate"
content.protection: Varied and sufficient.  At the crux section stepping off the ledge there are great wired stopper placements.
content.location: On "The Frigate" on it's S. face about in the middle of this exposure.  Next independent route line right of "Can Can".

content.description:
Delicate and burly at the same time.  The crux is exactly where you think it will be, the face above has good, sharp horizontals, and then there is a final throw to the top. 

  I've seen two different strategies used successfully:  ease up the flare, and power layback.
content.protection:
Good gear through the crux, then nothing on the face above (5.8-5.6).  Is there gear in the last ledge before the final crux? 

  For setting a TR, you can either solo up the chimney (4th class from the South), or jump down across the gaps from the Frigate walk-up.  Great gear under the block and one big cam across the chimney makes a strong, easy, stable anchor.
content.location: At the East end of the Frigate, facing the Lake, a flared slot through an overhang leads to a slabby face.

content.description: Thin, technical face left of The Pooper. Start off a block.

One of the better 5.5 leads at the Lake:  nice moves, good pro, wonderful summit. 

  On the Southeast side of the Frigate, a crack system heads up between the two summits.  From the base, move up a dihedral a little to the right, find some good pro, then move left and up into an alcove.  Kick high!  Getting into the alcove is probably the technical crux. 

  In the alcove, get some more bomber gear.  Kick high!  and pull around the little roof.  Head up to the summit on the right (North).
content.protection: Medium to large nuts, a couple of medium sized hexes or cams.
content.location: On the Southeast side of the Frigate.  "Walk off" (scramble) to the North.

content.description: Great mind bender. Run out sections culminate with a very committing move to a mantle top out.
content.protection: Standard gear or TR. The TR is good pieces all connected to one block on top. Practice your chimneying to get to the top to set TR.
content.location: Just around the corner from The Flying Dutchman. Start on the left corner, traverse right on the crack and do some mantle moves to the big horizontal break. Plan your attack for the top.

pathTokens: West Bluff 02 - Misery Rocks & The Pantry

content.description: The Frigate is an impressive-looking formation found just above the Porkchop Buttress and Dungeon Wall.  The overhanging west wall contains the challenging route "Pooper", and on the overhanging southeast wall you will find "Flying Dutchman", another difficult route.  Most other climbs here are easy to moderate.
